<item>
            <title>[LU-4987] Issues introduced by LU-4107</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-4987</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The patch from &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-4107&quot; title=&quot;luser_user.h is not C++ compatible&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-4107&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-4107&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, change &lt;a href=&quot;http://review.whamcloud.com/8033&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;8033&lt;/a&gt;, introduced two bugs:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1) Duplicate stdio.h include&lt;br/&gt;
2) Changing user-space api based only on one&apos;s compiler.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t even understand why folks thought LUSTRE_ANONYMOUS_UNION_NAME was the right thing to do.  The commenting is entirely inadequate here (&quot;Fix anonymous union.&quot;), so I am not even sure what problem they were trying to fix.  As far as I can tell, C++ has anonymous unions as well.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But regardless of the underlying problem, this does not seem like the solution we want.  This makes the user-space API change based only one&apos;s choice of compiler.  I don&apos;t think that is wise.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
